should be tied and regulated in such a way

33:05.000 --> 33:10.000
to satisfy the customer's needs as much as possible

33:10.000 --> 33:13.000
and meet the production requirements.

33:13.000 --> 33:16.000
The outcome of logistics or distribution of finished products

33:16.000 --> 33:23.000
is usually called the development of efficient channels of distribution of finished products to consumers.

33:23.000 --> 33:33.000
The purpose of this system is to satisfy the customer's needs in the finished product in the best way.

33:33.000 --> 33:36.000
Historically, in many companies, both before and still,

33:36.000 --> 33:43.000
the function of outgoing logistics was associated partially with the work and functioning of the marketing department.

33:43.000 --> 33:52.000
In this section, we will consider the main characteristics and principles of the function of outgoing logistics.

33:52.000 --> 34:00.000
As we have already considered, the main task of distribution is the rule 7N.

34:00.000 --> 34:07.000
The necessary product in the necessary quality should be delivered to the necessary place

34:07.000 --> 34:12.000
to the necessary customer at the necessary price.

34:12.000 --> 34:17.000
It will be useful to consider this rule in detail.

34:17.000 --> 34:22.000
Let's consider the example of the production of a package with apple juice.

34:22.000 --> 34:29.000
The necessary quality of the product means that the right transport,

34:29.000 --> 34:33.000
the right packaging for transportation, and the right price were chosen.

34:33.000 --> 34:41.000
The right price means that the right type of raw material, the right supplier, the right type of transport,

34:41.000 --> 34:45.000
the right time and place of delivery of the product to the production site,

34:45.000 --> 34:52.000
and the factor that the supplier provided the optimal delivery cost.

34:52.000 --> 35:01.000
Each of the seven elements shows what it can mean in the context of information,

35:01.000 --> 35:07.000
transportation, packaging, service, and management control.

35:07.000 --> 35:12.000
Many companies have several channels for distributing the finished product.

35:12.000 --> 35:17.000
The diagram below illustrates the possible distribution channels.

35:17.000 --> 35:24.000
Let's describe these channels in our example of apple juice production.

35:24.000 --> 35:30.000
The package with juice is delivered to the wholesale trading company from the manufacturer.

35:30.000 --> 35:36.000
Then the transport company delivers it to the distribution warehouses,

35:36.000 --> 35:45.000
from which restaurants, hotels, cafes, and supermarkets deliver the package to the final consumer.

35:45.000 --> 35:54.000
Simply put, the distribution channel is the path that the product goes from the manufacturer to the final consumer.

35:54.000 --> 35:57.000
Some distribution channels are simple.

35:57.000 --> 36:04.000
For example, the trading company buys an apple from a farmer and sells it to the consumer.

36:04.000 --> 36:06.000
Others are complicated.

36:06.000 --> 36:12.000
The same example, but the trading company buys an apple from a wholesale seller,

36:12.000 --> 36:17.000
who buys the product from the manufacturer.

36:17.000 --> 36:24.000
Then the product is sold not to the final consumer, but to the intermediaries in the delivery system,

36:24.000 --> 36:28.000
such as hotels, cafes, bars, and restaurants.

36:28.000 --> 36:32.000
The danger that lies in the management of the distribution system

36:32.000 --> 36:38.000
is the loss of communication between the supplier and the consumer.

36:38.000 --> 36:45.000
This can be avoided by building a vertical marketing system,

36:45.000 --> 36:52.000
in which all parties are interested in working to achieve the same goal.

36:52.000 --> 37:00.000
It should be noted that many companies consider the incoming and outgoing logistics to be different disciplines.

37:00.000 --> 37:07.000
Buyers and managers of distribution centers pay all their attention to the level of service.

37:07.000 --> 37:15.000
Supply and distribution specialists ensure that there are no residuals.

37:15.000 --> 37:23.000
Organizational structures do not see the whole picture of the business due to the lack of common information systems.

37:23.000 --> 37:30.000
Moving in the direction of creating product value,

37:30.000 --> 37:40.000
it should be noted that in the delivery system, which is designed to achieve the best result,

37:40.000 --> 37:49.000
the entire chain from the supplier to the buyer is monitored and controlled by everyone,

37:49.000 --> 37:53.000
without exception, including the members of this chain.

37:53.000 --> 37:59.000
Thus, the correct structure of the management of the delivery system allows you to control the entire system

37:59.000 --> 38:04.000
from the manufacturer to the buyer from start to finish.

38:04.000 --> 38:09.000
The advantages of combining the work of two systems,

38:09.000 --> 38:13.000
including the incoming and outgoing logistics,

38:13.000 --> 38:19.000
are transparency and 100% control of the entire supply chain,

38:19.000 --> 38:24.000
management of orders, downloads and deliveries in a single interface,

38:24.000 --> 38:29.000
and the determination of new opportunities for transportation,

38:29.000 --> 38:34.000
including on-the-go loads, delivery strategy, and so on.

38:34.000 --> 38:42.000
It is also necessary to remember the distribution requirement planning strategy,

38:42.000 --> 38:44.000
which is applicable in this case.

38:44.000 --> 38:51.000
Planning of distribution requirements, which is used to plan distribution channels,

38:51.000 --> 38:57.000
allows not only to coordinate the work of all systems,

38:57.000 --> 39:02.000
but also to synchronize the needs of the customer and the production capabilities.

39:02.000 --> 39:08.000
Thus, the main goal of creating effective distribution channels

39:08.000 --> 39:15.000
is to achieve the tasks set by close cooperation between the supplier and the consumer.

39:16.000 --> 39:20.000
The rapid development of the global economy in the 1980s and 1990s,

39:20.000 --> 39:24.000
in parallel with the growth of the application of computers and computer technologies

39:24.000 --> 39:27.000
in solving supply issues,

39:27.000 --> 39:36.000
led to a rapid growth of opportunities for data and document exchange between suppliers and manufacturers.

39:37.000 --> 39:44.000
This allowed both the buyer and the supplier to provide information to each other

39:44.000 --> 39:48.000
much more timely and accurately,

39:48.000 --> 39:54.000
while increasing the efficiency of work and reducing the bureaucratic burden,

39:54.000 --> 39:58.000
as well as increasing the quality of decisions made.

39:58.000 --> 40:03.000
In turn, the need for innovation and flexibility prompted many companies

40:03.000 --> 40:14.000
to introduce data exchange systems and thus change the existing organizational structure

40:14.000 --> 40:18.000
to reduce production costs.

40:18.000 --> 40:26.000
The idea is that a successful organization has the ability to generate and transmit the necessary knowledge

40:26.000 --> 40:30.000
and information both within the company and outside it.

40:31.000 --> 40:38.000
Often, the term data exchange is associated primarily with electronic information systems.

40:38.000 --> 40:43.000
This is not a coincidence, as in the modern world the necessary information

40:43.000 --> 40:49.000
obtained in the right time is the main asset of the company.

40:49.000 --> 40:52.000
The dynamics of the growth of companies in the world,

40:52.000 --> 40:58.000
which use information technologies very highly,

40:58.000 --> 41:01.000
can be seen in the table.

41:01.000 --> 41:05.000
The number of companies using data exchange systems is growing.

41:05.000 --> 41:11.000
In this section, we will consider some aspects of modern data transfer systems

41:11.000 --> 41:15.000
that are used to efficiently manage the supply system.

41:15.000 --> 41:23.000
Electronic data exchange is a process of transferring information

41:24.000 --> 41:30.000
and formal business transactions in a standard format between organizations.

41:30.000 --> 41:32.000
It has four forms.

41:32.000 --> 41:37.000
1. Transmission of electronic funds, banks, calculations with suppliers at the point of sale.

41:37.000 --> 41:41.000
2. Transmission of trading data, order for delivery,

41:41.000 --> 41:44.000
3. Downloading of data from the account.

41:44.000 --> 41:50.000
4. Transmission of technical data, drawings, graphics, interactive database.

41:50.000 --> 41:54.000
In our country, the rapid growth of electronic data exchange

41:54.000 --> 41:58.000
was caused by the growth of retail trading networks.

41:58.000 --> 42:04.000
As in the rest of the world, the use of barcoding as an element of electronic data exchange

42:04.000 --> 42:11.000
significantly accelerates the process of obtaining information within the supply system.

42:13.000 --> 42:18.000
You have probably seen and can imagine what barcoding is.

42:18.000 --> 42:23.000
These are parallel lines applied to the packaging or directly to the product.

42:23.000 --> 42:27.000
These parallel lines are read by a scanner,

42:27.000 --> 42:34.000
and the data encoded in this code is transmitted to the central computer.

42:34.000 --> 42:41.000
The scheme of operation of the barcoding system is quite simple.

42:41.000 --> 42:45.000
Let's take the example of the production of a package with apple juice.

42:45.000 --> 42:49.000
When the product arrives at the warehouse of the finished product,

42:49.000 --> 42:53.000
a barcode is applied to it.

42:53.000 --> 42:56.000
This barcode is read by a scanner,

42:56.000 --> 43:02.000
and the information about the packaging, the quantity of units of the product in the packaging,

43:02.000 --> 43:06.000
is sent to the main computer of the manufacturer.

43:06.000 --> 43:10.000
Then the manufacturer transfers this data to its supplier.

43:10.000 --> 43:14.000
After the physical product has arrived at the supplier's warehouse,

43:14.000 --> 43:17.000
the supplier is responsible for receiving the product.

43:17.000 --> 43:23.000
The scanner reads this information, and the information is sent to the supplier's computer.

43:23.000 --> 43:26.000
When the product is sold,

43:26.000 --> 43:32.000
for example, when you buy a particular product in a supermarket cashier,

43:32.000 --> 43:35.000
you see that the scanner reads the information.

43:35.000 --> 43:38.000
After the data is read and the payment is made,

43:38.000 --> 43:44.000
the information about the payment is sent to the supermarket's warehouse,

43:44.000 --> 43:48.000
and automatically to the supplier's warehouse.

43:48.000 --> 43:51.000
The supplier knows that the product has been sold,

43:51.000 --> 43:56.000
and a new order for delivery is automatically generated.

43:56.000 --> 44:04.000
There are several reasons for the increase in the use of electronic data exchange systems.

44:04.000 --> 44:10.000
The use of electronic data exchange systems becomes a standard practice in all companies,

44:10.000 --> 44:12.000
especially in the production sector.

44:12.000 --> 44:16.000
The desire to reduce the production cycle

44:16.000 --> 44:19.000
supports the use of electronic data exchange systems.

44:19.000 --> 44:24.000
The desire to reduce the production cycle

44:24.000 --> 44:29.000
supports the use of electronic data exchange systems.

44:29.000 --> 44:33.000
These systems also allow to create a higher additional cost

44:33.000 --> 44:37.000
and to free up human, financial and temporary resources

44:37.000 --> 44:40.000
that were previously involved in the process of data exchange.

44:40.000 --> 44:42.000
As mentioned above,

44:42.000 --> 44:47.000
the main focus of the delivery systems managers

44:47.000 --> 44:51.000
is on the process of data exchange.

44:51.000 --> 44:57.000
This is due to the ability to respond quickly to customer requests

44:57.000 --> 45:00.000
and to information about deliveries.

45:00.000 --> 45:10.000
These systems are called ERP, Enterprise Resource Planning,

45:10.000 --> 45:16.000
which is a system of resource planning.

45:16.000 --> 45:22.000
The delivery systems are characterized by the following functions.

45:23.000 --> 45:26.000
The management of stocks,

45:26.000 --> 45:28.000
purchase,

45:28.000 --> 45:30.000
product configurator,

45:30.000 --> 45:32.000
delivery system planning,

45:32.000 --> 45:34.000
production forecasting,

45:34.000 --> 45:36.000
quality control,

45:36.000 --> 45:38.000
processing of claims,

45:38.000 --> 45:40.000
calculation of commission discounts.

45:40.000 --> 45:46.000
The system of data storage about suppliers and buyers,

45:46.000 --> 45:50.000
the so-called general corporate memory of the enterprise,

45:50.000 --> 45:55.000
is often used by many employees of the procurement department

45:55.000 --> 46:00.000
as a database for choosing suppliers of a particular product

46:00.000 --> 46:06.000
in order to reduce the time for searching and increase the efficiency of their work.

46:06.000 --> 46:07.000
In conclusion,

46:07.000 --> 46:10.000
in order to understand the importance of the resource planning system

46:10.000 --> 46:12.000
for managing the delivery system,

46:12.000 --> 46:15.000
it is important to understand and characterize the main tasks

46:15.000 --> 46:18.000
that are set by the procurement system managers.

46:18.000 --> 46:24.000
One of the main tasks is to reduce the bureaucratic waste,

46:24.000 --> 46:27.000
which allows to release human resources.

46:27.000 --> 46:31.000
Reducing the workforce required for processing information

46:31.000 --> 46:38.000
allows to reduce the time required for processing from 15 to 40%.

46:38.000 --> 46:44.000
Accelerating the development of the integrated supply and raw material management system

46:44.000 --> 46:49.000
allows to manage the raw material supplies of the buyer.

46:49.000 --> 46:52.000
The third party trading network is used.

46:52.000 --> 46:56.000
At the same time, the intensity of the interaction between the buyer and the department

46:56.000 --> 46:59.000
that consumes raw material and suppliers increases.

46:59.000 --> 47:05.000
Electronic data exchange also helps to significantly reduce the total overhead costs.

47:05.000 --> 47:11.000
Some advantages of the introduction of electronic data exchange are given below.

47:11.000 --> 47:14.000
Electronic payment systems,

47:14.000 --> 47:17.000
purchasing without the use of paper carriers,

47:17.000 --> 47:20.000
professionalism in purchasing,

47:20.000 --> 47:22.000
growth of productivity,

47:22.000 --> 47:24.000
reduction of the level of stocks,

47:24.000 --> 47:27.000
reduction of the time for processing orders,

47:27.000 --> 47:31.000
creating an improved connection with suppliers and consumers,

47:31.000 --> 47:34.000
obtaining reliable and fast information,

47:34.000 --> 47:37.000
increased accuracy of data,

47:37.000 --> 47:40.000
support of the barcoding system.

47:40.000 --> 47:43.000
However, along with the advantages,

47:43.000 --> 47:48.000
it is necessary to note the significant difficulties that arise before companies

47:48.000 --> 47:53.000
in the process of introducing electronic data exchange systems.

47:53.000 --> 48:00.000
Some companies make decisions about gradual automation of processes,

48:00.000 --> 48:06.000
other companies start a business right away

48:06.000 --> 48:12.000
and at the very beginning introduce automated accounting and management systems.

48:12.000 --> 48:15.000
The difficulties are the following.

48:15.000 --> 48:17.000
The cost of software.

48:17.000 --> 48:24.000
Very often companies face this difficulty because they do not see the whole picture

48:24.000 --> 48:32.000
and buy a small module that can cover or solve the problem of a separate site,

48:32.000 --> 48:38.000
but does not solve the problem of the whole system or the whole organization.

48:38.000 --> 48:42.000
The next problem is the cost of the program.

48:42.000 --> 48:45.000
This includes the services of consultants,

48:45.000 --> 48:48.000
training of staff,

48:48.000 --> 48:50.000
modernization of equipment,

48:50.000 --> 48:52.000
purchase of new equipment,

48:52.000 --> 48:55.000
reorganization of existing workplaces,

48:55.000 --> 48:58.000
laying of networks, communications and so on.

48:58.000 --> 49:02.000
One of the difficulties of non-material nature

49:02.000 --> 49:08.000
can be attributed to the resistance of existing staff to new introductions.

49:08.000 --> 49:13.000
So, people who are used to working with the old system,

49:13.000 --> 49:19.000
can resist the introduction of new processes,

49:19.000 --> 49:22.000
especially if it is related to the dismissal of staff

49:22.000 --> 49:26.000
or the reorganization of the company as a whole.

49:26.000 --> 49:29.000
The reorganization of business processes of the enterprise,

49:29.000 --> 49:33.000
both separate and the whole company as a whole.

49:33.000 --> 49:38.000
And the last, but one of the most significant problems

49:38.000 --> 49:42.000
is the coordination of certain functions of the system

49:42.000 --> 49:47.000
between all departments, between all elements of the company.

49:47.000 --> 49:52.000
Each user of the same information should receive it on time

49:52.000 --> 49:56.000
and should receive exactly what is necessary.

49:56.000 --> 49:58.000
I will give an example.

49:58.000 --> 50:02.000
At the time of sale of a unit of finished product,

50:02.000 --> 50:06.000
the financial department, the procurement department, the sales department,

50:06.000 --> 50:09.000
each should see in their own way,

50:09.000 --> 50:15.000
from their side, this element, this operation.

50:15.000 --> 50:17.000
That is, for the financial department,

50:17.000 --> 50:21.000
the implementation of the product took place and money should be received.

50:21.000 --> 50:24.000
For the sales department, it is a disbursement.

50:24.000 --> 50:28.000
For the supply department, it is a command to purchase raw materials

50:28.000 --> 50:32.000
for the production of a new unit of product.

50:32.000 --> 50:35.000
As you can see from the above,

50:35.000 --> 50:40.000
the process of managing electronic data exchange systems

50:40.000 --> 50:44.000
is quite attractive from the point of view of enterprise management.

50:44.000 --> 50:50.000
But, in turn, it is very difficult from the point of view of the implementation

50:50.000 --> 50:55.000
of this system for production and its launch.

50:55.000 --> 51:00.000
Nevertheless, the main goal that the company pursues

51:00.000 --> 51:03.000
by implementing an electronic data exchange system

51:03.000 --> 51:08.000
is quality and timely service of the customer.

51:08.000 --> 51:12.000
All of the above allows us to understand how the system works,

51:12.000 --> 51:14.000
what its main components are,

51:14.000 --> 51:18.000
how effective this system works,

51:18.000 --> 51:22.000
how effective the operation of one or another element is.

51:22.000 --> 51:24.000
Do you know how it works?

51:24.000 --> 51:32.000
If not, you risk losing the relationship between the supplier and the customer,

51:32.000 --> 51:38.000
reducing the company's cost and actually losing control over the costs.

51:38.000 --> 51:41.000
The lack of information on how your supply system works

51:41.000 --> 51:47.000
and how effectively it works is particularly dangerous for those activities

51:47.000 --> 51:53.000
where the supply system is the basis of business operation.

51:53.000 --> 51:58.000
This includes production, retail and wholesale companies.

51:58.000 --> 52:03.000
The danger is so great that mistakes and lack of information

52:03.000 --> 52:05.000
can lead to bankruptcy of the company.

52:05.000 --> 52:07.000
There is a saying,

52:07.000 --> 52:10.000
if you cannot measure, you cannot correct.

52:10.000 --> 52:16.000
Very rarely there are programs that would allow to measure

52:16.000 --> 52:21.000
the work and efficiency of the system and the supply in general,

52:21.000 --> 52:26.000
that would help to show the whole picture of the system.

52:26.000 --> 52:30.000
They would be quite clear and simple

52:30.000 --> 52:36.000
and would point to the source of the problem in the system.

52:36.000 --> 52:38.000
The reason is simple.

52:38.000 --> 52:42.000
Creating a strong, effective and understandable supply system

52:42.000 --> 52:46.000
is a very complex process in itself.

52:46.000 --> 52:51.000
Even the process of matching the indicators of efficiency measurement

52:51.000 --> 52:56.000
between different departments, between the financial,

52:56.000 --> 53:00.000
between the production and the supply departments

53:00.000 --> 53:02.000
is a complex process in itself.

53:02.000 --> 53:10.000
Moreover, automating it makes it even more complicated.

53:10.000 --> 53:14.000
The main problem is the matching of the criteria.

53:14.000 --> 53:19.000
The indicator of efficiency for the financial department,

53:19.000 --> 53:23.000
what the financial department does,

53:23.000 --> 53:26.000
is not always the same as the sales department.

53:26.000 --> 53:30.000
And the fact that the sales department is not always

53:30.000 --> 53:35.000
a sufficient or correct criterion for the assessment of the production.

53:35.000 --> 53:40.000
I suggest you think about the criteria for the assessment of the work

53:40.000 --> 53:42.000
that is used at your enterprise.

53:42.000 --> 53:47.000
Surely, in many companies there are surveys

53:47.000 --> 53:53.000
for the assessment of the level of work of the sales department,

53:53.000 --> 53:59.000
the assessment of the level of work of the suppliers,

53:59.000 --> 54:03.000
how they interact with each other.

54:03.000 --> 54:06.000
Unfortunately, in most organizations,

54:06.000 --> 54:12.000
they pay attention only to the financial indicators of the system.

54:12.000 --> 54:17.000
This is not surprising, because the financial reports

54:17.000 --> 54:24.000
and financial indicators are indicators of the work of the entire company as a whole.

54:24.000 --> 54:29.000
But the assessment of the work of the supply system

54:29.000 --> 54:34.000
should not be limited to digital values,

54:34.000 --> 54:37.000
only financial indicators.

54:38.000 --> 54:45.000
Financial indicators do not reflect the picture at this particular time,

54:45.000 --> 54:50.000
or they speak about the picture, about the results of the work already done.

54:50.000 --> 54:56.000
But financial indicators cannot reflect the efficiency of the system in the future.

54:56.000 --> 55:04.000
Moreover, for example, for companies whose shares are traded

55:04.000 --> 55:07.000
on the New York stock exchange,

55:07.000 --> 55:11.000
after a series of corporate scandals in the late 1990s,

55:11.000 --> 55:20.000
standards were introduced, which must be implemented in all companies

55:20.000 --> 55:23.000
whose shares are traded on the stock exchange.

55:23.000 --> 55:29.000
This document is called the Sarbanes-Oxley Act of 2002.

55:30.000 --> 55:34.000
The document describes the main requirements for accounting,

55:34.000 --> 55:38.000
spending, fairness of financial reporting as a whole.

55:38.000 --> 55:47.000
A lot of attention is paid to the implementation and administration of documentation,

55:47.000 --> 55:53.000
control, procedures and figures obtained.

55:53.000 --> 55:56.000
Therefore, the main requirement of this Act

55:56.000 --> 56:00.000
is the correct and effective construction of control procedures in the company.

56:00.000 --> 56:07.000
But if the financial indicators of the system can help determine

56:07.000 --> 56:13.000
the degree of influence of the supply system on the financial state of the company,

56:13.000 --> 56:18.000
then I believe that these criteria may not be applicable

56:18.000 --> 56:22.000
to measure the performance of the system as a whole.

56:22.000 --> 56:24.000
The answer lies on the surface.

56:24.000 --> 56:31.000
The financial indicators represent the performance of the company in the past

56:31.000 --> 56:34.000
and do not give an opportunity to see the future.

56:34.000 --> 56:40.000
Also, the financial indicators do not provide us with non-financial information,

56:40.000 --> 56:45.000
such as the level of service, customer service,

56:45.000 --> 56:49.000
or the quality of the order for delivery.

56:49.000 --> 56:55.000
Is it really so important to measure the performance of the system and delivery?

56:55.000 --> 56:57.000
Of course.

56:57.000 --> 57:02.000
Especially for novice companies, it is very important to understand

57:02.000 --> 57:07.000
and determine at the initial stage what criteria,

57:07.000 --> 57:12.000
